\series medium
(Strong Maximum Principle)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in C^{2}\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

 be a harmonic function on an open and connected subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\subseteq\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 If a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in\Omega$
\end_inset

 with
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
u\left(x_{0}\right) & =\sup_{x\in\Omega}\left(u\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

or
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
u\left(x_{0}\right) & =\inf_{x\in\Omega}\left(u\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

exists, then 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Proof
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $-u$
\end_inset

 is also harmonic, it suffices to consider the case 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(x_{0}\right)=\sup_{\Omega}\left(u\right)$
\end_inset

, so assume
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
u\left(x_{0}\right) & =\sup_{\Omega}\left(u\right)=:M
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and define:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Omega_{M} & :=\left\{ x\in\Omega\big|u\left(x\right)=M\right\} 
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Clearly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{M}$
\end_inset

 is not empty, because 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in\Omega_{M}$
\end_inset

.
 By continuity, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{M}$
\end_inset

 is closed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 with respect to the relative topology.
 Thus it suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{M}$
\end_inset

 is open.
 Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\Omega_{M}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(y\right)=M$
\end_inset

, and choose 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in\mathbb{R}_{>0}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{r}\left(y\right)\subseteq\Omega$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =u\left(y\right)-M\sr ={\text{mean value}}{\text{property}}\frac{1}{\omega_{n}r^{n}}\int_{B_{r}\left(y\right)}\underbrace{\left(u\left(x\right)-M\right)}_{\le0}\dd\mu\left(x\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(x\right)\le M$
\end_inset

, the integrand is non-positive and continuous.
