\begin_layout Standard
A function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\Omega\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is called 
\emph on
Hölder continuous
\emph default
 with exponent 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, if holds:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\norm u_{C^{0,\alpha}\left(\Omega\right)} & :=\norm u_{C^{0}\left(\Omega\right)}+\sup_{x\not=y\in\Omega}\left(\frac{u\left(x\right)-u\left(y\right)}{\norm{x-y}^{\alpha}}\right)<\infty
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We often use the short notation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\norm ._{C^{0,\alpha}\left(\Omega\right)} & =:\norm ._{0,\alpha}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Obviously holds 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{0,\alpha}\left(\Omega\right)\subseteq C^{0}\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $C^{0,0}\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

 are bounded continuous functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $C^{0,1}\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

 are Lipschitz continuous functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This can also be defined locally: 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in C_{\text{loc}}^{0,\alpha}\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

 means that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\Omega$
\end_inset

 exists a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq\Omega$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\big|_{U}\in C^{0,\alpha}\left(U\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A typical example is 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(x\right)=\sqrt{\abs x}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[-1,1\right]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in C^{0,\frac{1}{2}}\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
C^{k,\alpha}\left(\Omega\right) & :=\left\{ f\in C^{k}\bigg|\DD^{\beta}f\in C^{0,\alpha}\fall_{\text{multi-index }\beta,\abs{\beta}\le k}\right\} \\
\norm f_{k,\alpha} & =\sum_{\beta,\abs{\beta}\le k}\norm{\DD^{\beta}f}_{0,\alpha}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

